==English==
{{rfv}}{{rfc}}

===Etymology===

From liminal (Latin ''limin-'', ''limen'') meaning "threshold"; and centric (medieval Latin ''–centricus'', Latin ''centrum'') meaning “a central position”

===Adjective===

'''liminocentric'''
# spatial or systemic configurations in which features such as thresholds (or extremities/edges) simultaneously exhibit attributes of the features of centralisation;
# in topology: shapes where extremities may be considered simultaneously as focal points, or as identical to the focal points;
# an indentity between the very small and very large such that both are for all intents and purposes identical, that is, indistinguishable.

===Examples===
* <u>Topology</u>: 
**The torus<sup>1</sup>. e.g. “The torus is a liminocentric composition”

* <u>Philosophy</u>: 
** In politics. e.g. “participatory democracy can be considered a liminocentric form of social organisation”; 
** As illustrative analogy/metaphor. e.g. “like a recursive set of Chinese Boxes<sup>2</sup>, this thesis postulates a liminocentric chain of cause and effect”



: 1. ''The [[torus]]: a three-dimensional doughnut-shaped surface revolving around itself''

: 2. ''[[Chinese boxes]]: a set of boxes of graduated size, each fitting inside the next larger one''